    phoenician_orthography_phonology_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Merger of Gutturals</strong></td><td>Guttural consonants (like ·∏• and  ø) merged phonetically in early Phoenician and were represented by the letter <code class='phoenician'>ê§á</code> (·∏§et).</td><td>The name ·∏§am is represented as <code class='phoenician'>ê§áê§å</code> (·∏§M).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Merger of Interdentals</strong></td><td>Interdental sounds (like 'th' in 'thin' or 'then') disappeared and merged with nearby sibilants (≈°, z, ·π£).</td><td>The word for "went" (Proto-Semitic *·∏èahaba) likely became <em>z-b-</em> in Phoenician, reflecting the 'dh' to 'z' shift.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Use of Waw and Yod for Long Vowels</strong></td><td>The letters <code class='phoenician'>ê§Ö</code> (w) and <code class='phoenician'>ê§â</code> (y) are primarily used to indicate long vowels (like /≈´/, /ƒ´/, /≈ç/, and /ƒì/).</td><td>The word '≈çr' (light): <code class='phoenician'>ê§Äê§Öê§ì</code> ('WR).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
    phoenician_pronouns_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>3rd Person Singular Pronoun (he/she)</strong></td><td>The most common form for the 3rd person personal pronoun is <code class='phoenician'>ê§Ñê§Ä</code> (h'), used for both masculine ('he') and feminine ('she').</td><td>"He is the god": <code class='phoenician'>ê§Ñê§Ä ê§Ñê§Äê§ã</code> (h' h'l).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Possessive Suffix (his)</strong></td><td>The possessive suffix for 3rd person singular masculine is <code>-w</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ê§Ö</code>) or <code>-h</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ê§Ñ</code>) (in construct cases).</td><td>"His servant": <code class='phoenician'>ê§èê§Åê§Éê§Ö</code> ('bdw).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Object Suffix (them)</strong></td><td>The suffix for the 3rd person plural object is <code>-nm</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ê§çê§å</code>) or <code>-m</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ê§å</code>).</td><td>"He blessed them": <code class='phoenician'>ê§Åê§ìê§äê§çê§å</code> (brknm).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
    phoenician_noun_adjective_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>No Case Endings</strong></td><td>Phoenician does not retain the three case endings (nominative, accusative, genitive) of Proto-Semitic. The function of a word is determined by its context in the sentence.</td><td><code class='phoenician'>ê§åê§ãê§ä</code> (mlk) can be a subject, object, or possessor, pronounced /malk/ in all cases.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Construct State</strong></td><td>The first noun in a possessive chain (the "construct") appears without the definite article (<code>h-</code>), while the article is attached to the second noun if it is definite.</td><td>"The well of the king": <code class='phoenician'>ê§Åê§Äê§ì ê§Ñê§åê§ãê§ä</code> (b'r hmlk).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Irregular Plurals</strong></td><td>There are cases where the masculine plural ends in <code>-t</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ê§ï</code>), which is typically the feminine singular/plural ending.</td><td><em>mƒ´lakt</em> ("kingdoms" - a feminine plural).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
    phoenician_verb_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Nip'al Stem (Passive/Reflexive)</strong></td><td>This verb stem is formed by prefixing <code>n-</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ê§ç</code>) or <code>'n-</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ê§Äê§ç</code>) to the root and indicates a passive or reflexive action.</td><td>"He was saved/rescued" (Nip'al): <code class='phoenician'>ê§çê§ëê§ã</code> (n·π£l).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Infinitive Absolute</strong></td><td>The infinitive absolute (often of the Qatol pattern) is used to emphasize a verb. Its form remains unchanged regardless of subject or tense.</td><td>"He surely blessed": <code class='phoenician'>ê§Åê§ìê§ä ê§Åê§ìê§ä</code> (brk brk).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Imperative Mood</strong></td><td>The masculine singular command form is derived from the imperfect stem (Yiqtol) without the pronominal prefix.</td><td>"Rule!": <code class='phoenician'>ê§åê§ãê§ä</code> (mlk) (from <code>ymlk</code>).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
    phoenician_prepositions_particles_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Conjunction "w-" (and)</strong></td><td>The letter <code class='phoenician'>ê§Ö</code> (w-) is used for "and" and is attached to the following word. It can also mean "then" in narrative sequences.</td><td>"and he": <code class='phoenician'>ê§Öê§Ñê§Ä</code> (wh').</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Preposition "l-" (to/for)</strong></td><td>The letter <code class='phoenician'>ê§ã</code> (l-) is used for "to," "for," or to indicate possession in a nominal construction.</td><td>"I had" (lit. "to me was"): <code class='phoenician'>ê§ãê§â ê§äê§ç</code> (ly kn).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Relative Pronoun</strong></td><td>The relative pronoun is <code class='phoenician'>ê§Äê§î</code> ('≈°), meaning "which" or "that."</td><td>"The city that...": <code class='phoenician'>ê§èê§ì ê§Äê§î</code> ('r '≈°).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
